summary:
Iran war effectively closes Strait of Hormuz, the key Persian Gulf passage for 20% of world oil shipments. Gasoline prices rise worldwide. Governments draft plans to reopen the strait after fighting ends. Consumers and economies face higher energy costs and supply risks. This follows U.S. military strikes on 16 Iranian mine-laying vessels near the strait.

An Israeli strike killed seven people on central Beirut seafront early Thursday as Hezbollah fired missiles at Israel. Explosions damaged two oil tankers in the Persian Gulf off Iraq, killing one crew member and affecting global shipping lanes; further strikes expected. Pentagon officials reported $11.3 billion in U.S. costs for the first six days of airstrikes against Iran, excluding prior buildup expenses. Oil prices surged past $100 per barrel amid strikes on Beirut and Tehran.

Over 45 Democratic senators demanded details from the Trump administration on evidence linking the U.S. to a February 28 strike on Minab elementary school in Iran that killed 165, mostly children. In eastern Congo, Rwanda-backed rebels overran Congolese troops and entered Goma with gunfire and shelling; United Nations counts over one million displaced in the city, threatening the aid hub. NASA and SpaceX launched four astronauts on a Falcon 9 from Kennedy Space Center to retrieve Butch Wilmore and Suni Williams after nine months on the International Space Station; docking set for Saturday. A U.S. appeals court lifted a block on Trump executive orders halting federal diversity, equity and inclusion programs. Flash floods and landslides from heavy rains killed 30 in Gamo Zone highlands of southern Ethiopia. Rapid Support Forces drone attack killed 17 including students in Sudan White Nile State. Displaced Palestinians crossed a bisecting military zone to return to northern Gaza on foot."}
